<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="L-theory" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Theory &amp; Definitions</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      This section will introduce some background theory for the Limits module, as well as some important definitions.
    </p>
  </introduction>  
  
  <subsection xml:id="L-theory-L1">
    <title>L1: Limits Graphically/Numerically</title>
    <definition xml:id="def-limit">
      <title>Limit</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose the function <m>f(x)</m> is defined when <m>x</m> is near the input <m>a</m>. We write
          <me>
            \lim_{x\to a} f(x) = L
          </me>
          if we can make the values of <m>f(x)</m> arbitrarily close to <m>L</m> by restricting <m>x</m> to be sufficiently close to <m>a</m>, but not equal to <m>a</m> itself.
        </p>
        <p>
          In this case, we say that the <term>limit</term> of <m>f</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>a</m> is <m>L</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <definition xml:id="def-limit-left">
      <title>Left-Hand Limit</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose the function <m>f(x)</m> is defined when <m>x</m> is near the input <m>a</m>. We write
          <me>
            \lim_{x\to a^-} f(x) = L
          </me>
          if we can make the values of <m>f(x)</m> arbitrarily close to <m>L</m> by restricting <m>x</m> to be sufficiently close to <m>a</m>, using inputs <m>x \lt a</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          In this case, we say that the <term>left-hand limit</term> of <m>f</m> is <m>L</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <definition xml:id="def-limit-right">
      <title>Right-Hand Limit</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose the function <m>f(x)</m> is defined when <m>x</m> is near the input <m>a</m>. We write
          <me>
            \lim_{x\to a^+} f(x) = L
          </me>
          if we can make the values of <m>f(x)</m> arbitrarily close to <m>L</m> by restricting <m>x</m> to be sufficiently close to <m>a</m>, using inputs <m>x \gt a</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          In this case, we say that the <term>right-hand limit</term> of <m>f</m> is <m>L</m>. 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <definition xml:id="def-limit-infinite">
      <title>Infinite Limit</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose the function <m>f(x)</m> is defined when <m>x</m> is near the input <m>a</m>. We write
          <me>
            \lim_{x\to a^-} f(x) = \infty
          </me>
          if the outputs of <m>f</m> get larger and larger in the positive direction (increase without bound) as the input approaches <m>a</m> from the left. We write
          <me>
            \lim_{x\to a^-} f(x) = -\infty
          </me>
          if the outputs of <m>f</m> get larger and larger in the negative direction (decrease without bound) as the input approaches <m>a</m> from the right.
        </p>
        <p>
          We can replace "left-hand limit" with "right-hand limit" in the definition above, and the one-sided limit with a two-sided limit.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <definition xml:id="def-limit-infinity">
      <title>Limits at Infinity</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f</m> be a function defined on some interval <m>(a,\infty)</m>.  Then <m>\ds \lim_{x\to\infty} f(x) = L</m> means that the values of <m>f(x)</m> can be made arbitrarily close to <m>L</m> by requiring <m>x</m> to be a sufficiently large positive number.
        </p>
        <p>
          If <m>g</m> is defined on some interval <m>(-\infty,a)</m>, then <m>\ds \lim_{x\to-\infty} g(x) = L</m> means that the values of <m>g(x)</m> can be made arbitrarily close to <m>L</m> by requiring <m>x</m> to be a sufficiently large negative number.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="L-theory-L2">
    <title>L2: Limits Analytically</title>
    
      <theorem xml:id="limit-laws">
        <title> Limit Laws</title>
        <p>
          Suppose that <m>c</m> is a constant, and that the limits <m>\ds \lim_{x\to a} f(x)</m> and <m>\ds \lim_{x\to a}</m> exist.  Then,
          <dl>
            <li>
              <title>Sum/Difference Law</title>
              <p>
                <m>\ds \lim_{x\to a} [f(x) \pm g(x)] = \ds \lim_{x\to a} f(x) \pm \lim_{x\to a} g(x)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <title>Constant Multiple Law</title>
              <p>
                <m>\ds \lim_{x\to a} [cf(x)] = c\cdot \lim_{x\to a} f(x)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <title>Multiplication Law</title>
              <p>
                <m>\ds \lim_{x\to a} [f(x)\cdot g(x)] = \lim_{x\to a} f(x)\cdot \lim_{x\to a} g(x)</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <title>Division Law</title>
              <p>
                <m>\ds \lim_{x\to a} \dfrac{f(x)}{g(x)} = \dfrac{\ds \lim_{x\to a} f(x)}{\ds \lim_{x\to a} g(x)}</m>, provided that <m>\ds \lim_{x\to a} g(x)\neq 0</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <title>Exponent Law</title>
              <p>
                <m>\ds \lim_{x\to a} [f(x)]^n = \left[\lim_{x\to a} f(x)\right]^n</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <title>Constant Law</title>
              <p>
                <m>\ds \lim_{x\to a} c = c</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <title>Root Law</title>
              <p>
                <m>\ds \lim_{x\to a} [f(x)]^{1/n} = \left[\lim_{x\to a} f(x)\right]^{1/n}</m>, where <m>n</m>  is a positive integer (we assume the limit is positive if <m>n</m> is even)
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <title>Composition Law</title>
              <p>
                If <m>\ds \lim_{x\to L} h(x) = K</m> and <m>h(L) = K</m>, then <m>\ds \lim_{x\to a} f(h(x)) = K</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </dl>
        </p>
      </theorem>

      <theorem xml:id="direct-substitution">
        <title>Direct Substitution Property</title>
        <p>
          If <m>f</m> is a polynomial, rational, or algebraic function with <m>a</m> in the domain of <m>f</m>, then <m>\ds \lim_{x\to a} f(x) = f(a)</m>
        </p>
      </theorem>

  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="L-theory-L3">
    <title>L3: Vertical/Horizontal Asymptotes</title>
    
    <definition xml:id="def-limits-vertical">
      <title>Vertical Asymptote</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The vertical line <m>x = a</m> is called a <term>vertical asymptote</term> of the curve <m>y = f(x)</m> if at least one of the following statements is true:
						<me>
							\lim_{x\to a} f(x) = \infty \qquad \lim_{x\to a^-} f(x) = \infty \qquad \lim_{x\to a^+}f(x) = \infty
						</me>
						<me>
							\lim_{x\to a} f(x) = -\infty \qquad \lim_{x\to a^-} f(x) = -\infty \qquad \lim_{x\to a^+} f(x) = -\infty
						</me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <definition xml:id="def-limits-horizontal">
      <title>Horizontal Asymptote</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The line <m>y=L</m> is called a <term>horizontal asymptote</term> of the curve <m>y=f(x)</m> if either 
							<me>
								\lim_{x\to\infty} f(x) = L\qquad \text{or}\qquad \lim_{x\to -\infty} f(x) = L
							</me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="L-theory-facts">
    <title>Facts About Limits</title>
    
    <assemblage>
      <title>Existence of a Limit</title>
      <p>
        A function <m>f(x)</m> has a limit at <m>x=a</m> if and only if 
        <me>
          \lim_{x\to a^-} f(x) = \lim_{x\to a^+} f(x)
        </me>
        
      </p>
    </assemblage>

    <assemblage>
      <title>Function Existence at <m>a</m> vs. Limit at <m>a</m></title>
      <p>
        For a function <m>f(x)</m>, it may have a limit at <m>x=a</m>, even if <m>f(a)</m> does not exist.
      </p>
    </assemblage>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="L-theory-comments">
    <title>Other Comments</title>
    
    <assemblage>
      <title>A Word about Notation in General</title>
      <p>
        In mathematics, notation is the way you succinctly communicate your ideas.  Notation is part of the ``language'' of math; proper notation ensures proper communication.  Please pay very careful attention to how you and I write limits in and out of class.
      </p>
      <p>
        Notation can be a confusing aspect of mathematics- and that's ok.  It happens for Calculus I students and even for practicing mathematicians.  If you have any questions, please refer to your notes and/or ask me!  I am happy to help you navigate things that are confusing or don't make sense to you.
      </p>
    </assemblage>

    <assemblage>
      <title>The Meaning of the Symbol <m>\infty</m></title>
      <p>
        We use the notation <m>\infty</m> or <m>-\infty</m> to indicate a value which gets arbitrarily large.  In particular, <alert>infinity is not a number and should not be treated like one</alert>.
      </p>
    </assemblage>
      
  </subsection>
</section>